teers gave voice to their moral positions and religious values. She also examines how they invested their conversations, and mundane activities such as cooking, with personal meaning that in turn affected how they saw their own spiritual lives. Filled with vibrant storytelling and rich theoretical insights, Heaven's Kitchen shows faith as a living practice, reshaping our understanding of the role of religion in contemporary American life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aVolunteer workers in social servicexReligious lifezNew York (State)zNew YorkvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  areligion, religious studies, faith, belief, god, moral, ethical, spiritual, spirituality, questions, answers, new york city, nonprofit, nonreligious, organization, activist, advocate, aids, disease, end of life, volunteer, home cooked, meal delivery, values, cooking, storytelling, contemporary, modern, present day, america, american, seminary, kitchen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022604281740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226042831423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226042831/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles